# Task-Based Learning within a Project-Based Urban Ethnographic OER System

## 1. Conceptual positioning

This system integrates Task-Based Language Teaching (TBLT) and Project-Based Learning (PBL) within an urban ethnographic framework.

TBLT operates as the micro-level learning engine, while PBL provides the macro-level organizational structure.

Learning is therefore both task-driven and project-structured, embedded in real-world urban research contexts.

---

## 2. Core pedagogical model

The system is defined as:

> Project-Structured Task-Based Urban Ethnographic Learning

This model combines:

- task-based linguistic action (TBLT)
- project-based inquiry and production (PBL)
- ethnographic engagement with urban spaces
- multimodal and mediated meaning-making

---

## 3. Role of urban ethnography

Urban Linguistic Landscapes are approached as ethnographic fields.

Learners act as:

- observers of urban semiotic environments
- documenters of linguistic phenomena
- interpreters of sociocultural meaning
- producers of mediated representations

This aligns the system with practices similar to urban walking methodologies (e.g. “Paseo de Jane”-type approaches), where the city is read as a field of inquiry.

---

## 4. Dual-layer structure: tasks and project

The system operates through two interdependent layers:

### 4.1 Task layer (micro-structure)
Tasks structure learning processes into actionable units:

- observation
- interpretation
- mediation
- production

These tasks are short-cycle, iterative, and linguistically focused.

---

### 4.2 Project layer (macro-structure)
The project defines the overarching learning trajectory:

- urban exploration campaign
- multimodal documentation cycle
- curated artefact production
- OER publication process

The project gives coherence and purpose to individual tasks.

---

## 5. Task typology within the hybrid system

Tasks are embedded within the project and organised as follows:

### 5.1 Observation tasks
Engagement with urban linguistic landscapes.

- identifying linguistic artefacts
- capturing multimodal input
- mapping urban semiotic data

---

### 5.2 Interpretation tasks
Meaning construction from urban input.

- decoding signage and messages
- cultural and linguistic interpretation
- contextual inference

---

### 5.3 Mediation tasks
Transformation across languages and modes.

- translation and reformulation
- simplification/expansion of meaning
- adaptation for target audiences

---

### 5.4 Production tasks
Creation of multimodal artefacts.

- text-image compositions
- structured OER outputs
- spatially contextualised representations

---

## 6. Ethnographic learning cycle

The learning process follows an iterative ethnographic cycle:

1. Urban immersion (ULL exposure)
2. Data collection (visual + linguistic)
3. Interpretation and mediation
4. Artefact production
5. Reflection and recontextualisation
6. OER publication and reuse

This cycle mirrors urban ethnographic walking methodologies.

---

## 7. Multimodality as operational condition

All tasks operate across multiple semiotic modes:

- linguistic (written language)
- visual (signs, images, layout)
- spatial (urban positioning)
- digital (documentation and AR)

Meaning emerges through integration of these modalities.

---

## 8. Assessment integration

Evaluation is embedded within both task and project structures.

Criteria include:

- linguistic accuracy and development
- quality of mediation processes
- multimodal coherence
- ethnographic depth of interpretation
- reusability as OER artefact

Assessment functions as both pedagogical and analytical tool.

---

## 9. OER production logic

The final output of the system is not only learning achievement but also:

- reusable educational resources
- multimodal artefacts
- documented urban interpretations
- adaptable teaching materials

Learners become co-producers of Open Educational Resources.

---

## 10. System positioning within Layer 0

This module operationalises:

- Urban Linguistic Landscapes (Layer 1)
- Multimodality and mediation (Layer 3)
- AR contextualisation (Layer 4)
- OER production logic (Layer 5–6)

It functions as the operational bridge between theory and empirical implementation.

---

## 11. Final synthesis

This system is neither purely task-based nor purely project-based.

It is a hybrid pedagogical architecture in which:

- tasks structure linguistic action
- projects structure inquiry and coherence
- ethnography provides methodological grounding
- the urban environment provides authentic data
- learners act as researchers and producers of knowledge
